description:
File: lichen/subsys/lichen/app_interface/app_interface.c:387-400

  for (size_t i = 0U; i < sink_count; i++) {
      int ret;

      memset(status, 0, sizeof(*status));  // zeroes before EACH attempt
      ret = snapshot[i].get_status(status, snapshot[i].user_data);

      if (ret == 0) {
          return 0;
      }
      if (first_error == 0) {
          first_error = ret;
      }
  }
  return first_error;

The memset inside the loop zeroes the status struct before each provider attempt. This is correct for ensuring clean state per attempt.

However, if ALL providers fail, the caller receives:
- first_error indicating failure
- status struct zeroed from the last failed attempt

If any provider partially populated status before failing, that data is lost. The caller cannot distinguish between:
1. Provider returned error before writing anything
2. Provider wrote partial data then failed

This may be intentional design, but consider:
- Moving memset before the loop (single zero, preserve partial data from last attempt)
- Or document that status is undefined on error return
